The Fed says the press conference is aimed at increasing transparency. It?s more likely to be a tour de force in sleep-inducing obfuscation.The Federal Open Market Committee, the Fed?s policy group, will issue its statement at 1230 p.m. EDT, ahead of Big Ben?s 2:15 p.m. EDT date with the press. It is difficult to imagine that Big Ben will break new ground at the microphone, but there?s always hope. Jean-Claude Trichet, head of the European Central Bank, used a press briefing to signal that the ECB planned to raise rates this month, which it did early this month. (The ECB, like other central banks, has held press briefings for years.)The dollar?s recent weakness ? the dollar index is at a three-year low and the euro is at a fresh 52-week high ? underscores the belief that the Fed is in no rush to tighten its extraordinarily loose monetary policy. Our friends at Real Time Economics offer a nifty primer on how to interpret the words and phrases of Big Ben. (The over/under betting line for number of chuckles Big Ben gets: three.)The Fed, in its statement, is expected to say it will finish its $600 billion quantitative easing program (QE2) on schedule in June. It is also not expected to raise too many alarms about looming interest-rate moves. #text: By Christopher Hinton NEW YORK (Dow Jones) -- The vast, desolate tracks of Russian Siberia are home to one of the world's largest stands of untouched timber, full of red pine and larch coveted by the pulp and paper industry. wants to be, positioning itself in Asia, where paper and board production is expected to surpass output in the languishing North American market by 2015.

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Christopher Hinton NEW YORK (Dow Jones) -- MeadWestvaco Corp. said Wednesday it swung to a second-quarter profit on the back of its mill-based packaging business that benefited from increased prices and improved product mix. For the recent quarter, the Glen Allen, Va., consumer products packaging company said net income was $32 million, or 17 cents a share, up from a loss of $7 million, or 4 cents a share in the same period last year. Recent second-quarter earnings includes an after-tax charge of $5 million, or 3 cents a share, related after-tax charge for employee separation costs and facility closures, and a one-time cost of $5 million, or 3 cents a share, related to a cost-initiative program.

    session characterized by listless, rangebound trading as investors remained nervous about
    upcoming economic data and rising interest rates. With a long weekend ahead, market
    participants were even less willing to take on additional risk and kept positions close to
    the vest throughout Friday's session. Inside the market, brokerage stocks extended
    Thursday's losses as concerns continue to mount that the slow IPO calendar and diminishing
    trading volumes will take a significant bite into the earnings of Wall Street firms. The
    broader market saw the greatest weakness in the biotech, paper, oil service and paper
    sectors while utility stocks climbed. Internet and computer hardware stocks were the
    hardest hit sectors in the technology arena. The Dow Industrials shed 24.68 points, or 0.2
    percent, to 10,299.24. The Nasdaq Composite lost 0.20 point to 3,205.15 while the Nasdaq
    100 index, which encompasses the largest Nasdaq stocks by market capitalization, inched up

Headlines.Author: CBS.MarketWatch.com
Headlines.Headline: Profiting from the bear

#text:
Despite Wall Street's
        declines of the past several weeks, some mutual funds
        have been climbing. They are portfolios with a
        "bearish" perspective. While their
        hedging strategies may protect investors in a down
        market, the "bear" funds have gained only 12
        percent over this bull market's past seven years.
        But while the average fund lost 4.82 percent during a
        week in October, the Prudent Bear

fund rose 8.52 percent and
        the Rydex Ursa

fund rose 4.75 percent, the
        Christian Science Monitor reported. David Tice,
        president and founder of Dallas-based Prudent Bear, is
        felling optimistic in a pessimistic sort of way. "We
        believe the bear market has started. We believe it will
        require a substantial decline of more than 50 percent in
        order to wash out the excesses," the Monitor
        reported. Ursa portfolio manager Mike Byum
        is also upbeat, having seen his portfolio's assets rise
        from $260 to $514 million since October 1. He told
        the newspaper, "It's always nice to see investors
        doing well in down markets."
